-- Goedel Fixed Point in CredTT
--
-- NOTE: This file DEMONSTRATES the proof checker syntax.
-- The actual metatheory is formalized in agda/CredTT/Incompleteness.agda
--
-- LITERATURE: Hajek-Paris-Shepherdson, "The Liar Paradox and Fuzzy Logic" (2000)
-- The c = 1-c -> c = 1/2 result is standard in fuzzy logic self-reference.
--
-- Classical: G is undecidable (neither provable nor refutable)
-- CredTT: G has credence 1/2 (the fixed point of negation)
--
-- G = "G has credence 0" = "G is unprovable at credence 1"
-- If G @ c, then by G's content, c should equal 0
-- But if c = 0, then not G @ 1, so G @ 1 (contradiction)
-- Resolution: c = neg c, which has unique solution c = 1/2

-- Encode the Goedel sentence
encode G = Unprov_G

-- The Goedel sentence asserts its own unprovability
-- G <-> not Prov_1(G)
-- If Prov(G) @ c, then G's meaning implies c should satisfy c = neg c

-- Assume G at some credence c
postulate g : G 〔 c 〕

-- Self-reference: G claims "Prov(G) @ 0"
-- So if G @ c, then Prov(G) @ 0 should hold
derive g_claims : Prov_G_zero 〔 c 〕 from g by self_reference

-- But we assumed Prov(G) @ c, not 0
-- The only consistent resolution: c = neg c

-- Solve the fixpoint equation: c = neg c -> c = 1/2
fixpoint godel_c = ¬godel_c

-- The Goedel sentence has determinate credence 1/2
-- This is not undecidability - it's maximal uncertainty
-- At c = 1/2, "G is somewhat true" and "G is somewhat false" both hold
-- This is the unique stable equilibrium

-- Provability of G at credence 1/2
provable godel_provability : G 〔 1/2 〕

-- Key insight: Classical logic only has {0,1}
-- The equation c = neg c has no solution in {0,1}
-- Hence classical undecidability
-- But in [0,1], c = 1-c has the solution c = 1/2
